When you're 85, the chief side effect is finally realized: no one wants to work anymore. Once people hit about 70, they seem to lose all interest in going to work. Many of them just walk off the job: after all, everyone gets social security and Medicare now.
The government tries to force people to work, but it's not working.
 So Washington comes up with a plan. If you don't work, you don't get any social security or Medicare. You get nothing. And if you don't work, you don't get to vote.

When you're 85, the chief side effect is finally realized: no one wants to work anymore. Once people hit about 70, they seem to lose all interest in going to work. Many of them just walk off the job: after all, everyone gets social security and Medicare now.
The government tries to force people to work, but it's not working.

The plan works, but not in the way the government expected.

Your government decides to give the drug to all citizens under 26, but you and the rest of the "Lost Generations" are deemed too high-risk. When you're 85, the chief side effect is finally realized: no one wants to work anymore. Once people hit about 70, they seem to lose all interest in going to work. Many of them just walk off the job: after all, everyone gets social security and Medicare now.
The government tries to force people to work, but it's not working.
 So Washington comes up with a plan. If you don't work, you don't get any social security or Medicare. You get nothing. And if you don't work, you don't get to vote.
The plan works, but not in the way the government expected.
 Instead of going back to work, most people file for disability. Lawyers spring up that, for a few thou, will argue before a disability tribunal that work makes you anxious and depressed, hence mentally ill, which is a protected disability under the Federal Employment Statues.
The government tries to make it harder to get disability, but the lawyers just get better at their jobs.
 Soon, half the country is on disability. And

When you're 85, the chief side effect is finally realized: no one wants to work anymore. Once people hit about 70, they seem to lose all interest in going to work. Many of them just walk off the job: after all, everyone gets social security and Medicare now.
The government tries to force people to work, but it's not working.
 So Washington comes up with a plan. If you don't work, you don't get any social security or Medicare. You get nothing. And if you don't work, you don't get to vote.
The plan works, but not in the way the government expected.
 Instead of going back to work, most people file for disability. Lawyers spring up that, for a few thou, will argue before a disability tribunal that work makes you anxious and depressed, hence mentally ill, which is a protected disability under the Federal Employment Statues.
The government tries to make it harder to get disability, but the lawyers just get better at their jobs.
 Soon, half the country is on disability. And the orher half, well, let's just s

When you're 85, the chief side effect is finally realized: no one wants to work anymore. Once people hit about 70, they seem to lose all interest in going to work. Many of them just walk off the job: after all, everyone gets social security and Medicare now.
The government tries to force people to work, but it's not working.
 So Washington comes up with a plan. If you don't work, you don't get any social security or Medicare. You get nothing. And if you don't work, you don't get to vote.
The plan works, but not in the way the government expected.
 Instead of going back to work, most people file for disability. Lawyers spring up that, for a few thou, will argue before a disability tribunal that work makes you anxious and depressed, hence mentally ill, which is a protected disability under the Federal Employment Statues.
The government tries to make it harder to get disability, but the lawyers just get better at their jobs.
 Soon, half the country is on disability. And the other half, well, let's just say the other half are not model employees.
So what's the government to do?
 They're running out of money. NOt o

Your government decides to give the drug to all citizens under 26, but you and the rest of the "Lost Generations" are deemed too high-risk. When you're 85, the chief side effect is finally realized: no one wants to work anymore. Once people hit about 70, they seem to lose all interest in going to work. Many of them just walk off the job: after all, everyone gets social security and Medicare now.
The government tries to force people to work, but it's not working.
 So Washington comes up with a plan. If you don't work, you don't get any social security or Medicare. You get nothing. And if you don't work, you don't get to vote.
The plan works, but not in the way the government expected.
 Instead of going back to work, most people file for disability. Lawyers spring up that, for a few thou, will argue before a disability tribunal that work makes you anxious and depressed, hence mentally ill, which is a protected disability under the Federal Employment Statues.
The government tries to make it harder to get disability, but the lawyers just get better at their jobs.
 Soon, half the country is on disability. And the other half, well, let's just say the other half are not model employees.
So what's the government to do?
 They're running out of money. Not onl;y that, but garbahg

When you're 85, the chief side effect is finally realized: no one wants to work anymore. Once people hit about 70, they seem to lose all interest in going to work. Many of them just walk off the job: after all, everyone gets social security and Medicare now.
The government tries to force people to work, but it's not working.
 So Washington comes up with a plan. If you don't work, you don't get any social security or Medicare. You get nothing. And if you don't work, you don't get to vote.
The plan works, but not in the way the government expected.
 Instead of going back to work, most people file for disability. Lawyers spring up that, for a few thou, will argue before a disability tribunal that work makes you anxious and depressed, hence mentally ill, which is a protected disability under the Federal Employment Statues.
The government tries to make it harder to get disability, but the lawyers just get better at their jobs.
 Soon, half the country is on disability. And the other half, well, let's just say the other half are not model employees.
So what's the government to do?
 They're running out of money. Not onl;y that, but garbahge is going uncollected and tr

When you're 28, science discovers a drug that stops all effects of aging, creating immortality. Your government decides to give the drug to all citizens under 26, but you and the rest of the "Lost Generations" are deemed too high-risk. When you're 85, the chief side effect is finally realized: no one wants to work anymore. Once people hit about 70, they seem to lose all interest in going to work. Many of them just walk off the job: after all, everyone gets social security and Medicare now.
The government tries to force people to work, but it's not working.
 So Washington comes up with a plan. If you don't work, you don't get any social security or Medicare. You get nothing. And if you don't work, you don't get to vote.
The plan works, but not in the way the government expected.
 Instead of going back to work, most people file for disability. Lawyers spring up that, for a few thou, will argue before a disability tribunal that work makes you anxious and depressed, hence mentally ill, which is a protected disability under the Federal Employment Statues.
The government tries to make it harder to get disability, but the lawyers just get better at their jobs.

So what's the government to do?
 They're running out of money. Not onl;y that, but garbahge is going uncollected and trains no longer run on time.

When you're 28, science discovers a drug that stops all effects of aging, creating immortality. Your government decides to give the drug to all citizens under 26, but you and the rest of the "Lost Generations" are deemed too high-risk. When you're 85, the chief side effect is finally realized: no one wants to work anymore. Once people hit about 70, they seem to lose all interest in going to work. Many of them just walk off the job: after all, everyone gets social security and Medicare now.
The government tries to force people to work, but it's not working.
 So Washington comes up with a plan. If you don't work, you don't get any social security or Medicare. You get nothing. And if you don't work, you don't get to vote.
The plan works, but not in the way the government expected.
 Instead of going back to work, most people file for disability. Lawyers spring up that, for a few thou, will argue before a disability tribunal that work makes you anxious and depressed, hence mentally ill, which is a protected disability under the Federal Employment Statues.
The government tries to make it harder to get disability, but the lawyers just get better at their jobs.
 Soon, half the country is on disability. And the other half, well, let's just say the other half are not model employees.

Your government decides to give the drug to all citizens under 26, but you and the rest of the "Lost Generations" are deemed too high-risk. When you're 85, the chief side effect is finally realized: no one wants to work anymore. Once people hit about 70, they seem to lose all interest in going to work. Many of them just walk off the job: after all, everyone gets social security and Medicare now.
The government tries to force people to work, but it's not working.
 So Washington comes up with a plan. If you don't work, you don't get any social security or Medicare. You get nothing. And if you don't work, you don't get to vote.
The plan works, but not in the way the government expected.
 Instead of going back to work, most people file for disability. Lawyers spring up that, for a few thou, will argue before a disability tribunal that work makes you anxious and depressed, hence mentally ill, which is a protected disability under the Federal Employment Statues.
The government tries to make it harder to get disability, but the lawyers just get better at their jobs.
 Soon, half the country is on disability. And the other half, well, let's just say the other half are not model employees.
So what's the government to do?
 They're running out of money. Not only that, but garbage is going uncollected and planes and trains no longer run on time.

On the other hand, wars have stopped because no one wants to fight in or lead them. And there's no more crime, because no one can be bothered to commit it.
So the government decides to do what it should have done in the first place: it gives the danoidote t everyone.

When you're 28, science discovers a drug that stops all effects of aging, creating immortality. Your government decides to give the drug to all citizens under 26, but you and the rest of the "Lost Generations" are deemed too high-risk. When you're 85, the chief side effect is finally realized: no one wants to work anymore. Once people hit about 70, they seem to lose all interest in going to work. Many of them just walk off the job: after all, everyone gets social security and Medicare now.
The government tries to force people to work, but it's not working.
 So Washington comes up with a plan. If you don't work, you don't get any social security or Medicare. You get nothing. And if you don't work, you don't get to vote.
The plan works, but not in the way the government expected.
 Instead of going back to work, most people file for disability. Lawyers spring up that, for a few thou, will argue before a disability tribunal that work makes you anxious and depressed, hence mentally ill, which is a protected disability under the Federal Employment Statues.
The government tries to make it harder to get disability, but the lawyers just get better at their jobs.
 Soon, half the country is on disability. And the other half, well, let's just say the other half are not model employees.

When you're 28, science discovers a drug that stops all effects of aging, creating immortality. Your government decides to give the drug to all citizens under 26, but you and the rest of the "Lost Generations" are deemed too high-risk. When you're 85, the chief side effect is finally realized: no one wants to work anymore. Once people hit about 70, they seem to lose all interest in going to work. Many of them just walk off the job: after all, everyone gets social security and Medicare now.
The government tries to force people to work, but it's not working.
 So Washington comes up with a plan. If you don't work, you don't get any social security or Medicare. You get nothing. And if you don't work, you don't get to vote.
The plan works, but not in the way the government expected.
 Instead of going back to work, most people file for disability. Lawyers spring up that, for a few thou, will argue before a disability tribunal that work makes you anxious and depressed, hence mentally ill, which is a protected disability under the Federal Employment Statues.
The government tries to make it harder to get disability, but the lawyers just get better at their jobs.
 Soon, half the country is on disability. And the other half, well, let's just say the other half are not model employees.
